Issues.Body:
I need help


### Overview of the problem

This is about the Bulma **CSS framework** 

### Description

I need to make a sub-navbar (below the navbar) in a mobile version.
I have managed to make this sub-navbar show up in the app, but the problem is that this new piece is on top of the content below. As if it were not an extension of the navbar
Please refer to the example `https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Pldz2IiQPWr_GhKSX1jeof2mZ3Ga4Ywd/view?usp=sharing`
the sub-navbar is that small blue container, sized as the navbar

### Steps to Reproduce


1. Create the navbar component
2. use the brand and menu component
3. below the </Menu> tag create a container (just a simple` <div>`) . This `<div>` will be the sub-navbar


### Expected behavior

the sub-navbar should not overlap the content below (body)

### Actual behavior


The sub-navbar overlaps the content of the body



#####################################################

I'm using ROR with reactJS

```
<%= react_component("common/AppNavbar", districts: @global_districts, sdistrict: session[:district], search_param: search_param, nil_current_user: current_user.nil?) %>
    <main> 
    <%= yield %>
    </main>
```

this is how I call the component and the section below.

####################################################
####################################################

this is how I implement the sub-navbar

```
</Menu>
            <div className="is-hidden-desktop mini-navbar is-inline-flex">
              <i
                id="location-icon"
                className="fas fa-map-marker-alt is-size-6 has-margin-left-10"
              ></i>
              <select id="select2" className="has-margin-left-5 " onChange={this.onNormalChange} value={selectedDistrict}>
                <option value="">
                  Todo Maule
                </option>
                {this.props.districts.map((district) => (
                  <option key={district.id} value={district.name}>
                    {district.name}
                  </option>
                ))}
              </select>
            </div>
          </Container>
        </Navbar>
```

css

```
.mini-navbar {
  height: 30px;
  display: inline-flex;
  width: 100%;
  position: relative;
  background-color: #283348;
  color: white;
  span {
    font-size: small;
  }
  #select2 {
    background-color: #283348;
    color: white;
    // height: auto;
    border: none;
    width: 95px;
    overflow: auto;
  }
  strong {
    color: white;
  }
  #location-icon {
    margin-top: 5.9px;
  }
  #drop-icon {
    margin-top: 5px;
  }
}
```

####################################################
####################################################

I already tried with margin and padding properties, with no luck.

Bulma 0.9.0
Tested with latest Chrome, Firefox, Safari on macOS 10.15.6 getting the same behaviors.

This happens only in shadow dom. Without specifying `box-sizing`, it seems it defaults to `context-box`, and the button is much bigger than it should be, unless manually set to `border-box`.

I am not sure if this is the expected behavior or a bug.

```html
<body>
  <test-one></test-one>
  <test-two></test-two>
</body>
```

```javascript
customElements.define('test-one', class extends HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    super();

    const node = document.createElement('template');
    node.innerHTML = `
<style>
@import 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bulma@0.9.0/css/bulma.css';
* {
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
</style>
<button class="button is-primary">border-box</button>
`;
    this.attachShadow({
      mode: 'open'
    }).appendChild(node.content);
  }
});



customElements.define('test-two', class extends HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    super();

    const node = document.createElement('template');
    node.innerHTML = `
<style>
@import 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bulma@0.9.0/css/bulma.css';

</style>
<button class="button is-danger">probably content-box</button>
`;
    this.attachShadow({
      mode: 'open'
    }).appendChild(node.content);
  }
});
```

